    <patterns>
      <pattern name="Existing `AnalysisChunk` record + factories" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Models/Ai/AnalysisChunk.cs">
        Read the file FIRST. The record is a positional `record` with
        `[property: JsonPropertyName(...)]` attributes on each parameter and four static
        factory methods (`FromContent`, `Completed(string)`, `Completed(DocumentAnalysisResult)`,
        `FromError`). Extend by: (a) appending a new parameter `FieldDelta? Delta`
        with `[property: JsonPropertyName("delta")]` + `[property: JsonIgnore(Condition = JsonIgnoreCondition.WhenWritingNull)]`
        (default value `= null` to preserve back-compat call sites); (b) adding a new
        nested or sibling `record FieldDelta(string Path, string Content, int Sequence)`
        in the same file with `[property: JsonPropertyName(...)]` on each parameter; (c)
        adding a new static factory `AnalysisChunk.FromDelta(string path, string content, int sequence)`
        returning a `new AnalysisChunk(Type: "delta", Content: string.Empty, Done: false, Delta: new FieldDelta(path, content, sequence))`.
        Preserve XML doc comments and update the `&lt;summary&gt;` to mention the `"delta"` event type.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Wizard consumer back-compat shape" location="src/solutions/LegalWorkspace/src/components/SummarizeFiles/summarizeService.ts">
        Lines ~80â€“100 contain the discriminant filter: `if (chunk.type === 'progress')`,
        `else if (chunk.type === 'result')`, `else if (chunk.type === 'error')`,
        `else if (chunk.done)`. An unknown discriminant (`"delta"`) falls through every
        branch and the loop continues â€” this is the back-compat contract. Mirror this
        parser shape in the wizard-consumer-parity test (in C# or pseudo-form) to lock
        in the expected behavior.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Serialization round-trip test style" location="tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/Models/Ai/BuilderSseEventsTests.cs">
        Existing tests in this folder use `System.Text.Json.JsonSerializer` with
        `PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.CamelCase`, `FluentAssertions` for
        assertions, and `Xunit` `[Fact]`s. Follow the same conventions for the new
        `AnalysisChunkTests` (or `AnalysisChunkFieldDeltaTests`) file: cover
        (a) `FromDelta` factory output; (b) serializeâ†’deserializeâ†’re-serialize byte-equality
        for both delta and non-delta variants; (c) `Delta = null` produces JSON without
        a `"delta"` property.
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      R5 ships a chat-driven "Summarize a Document" vertical slice. The Workspace tab
      hosts a new `StructuredOutputStreamWidget` (task 017) that renders structured AI
      output progressively as Azure OpenAI Structured Outputs emits JSON tokens. The
      BFF side (task 006) runs an incremental JSON parser over the streaming completion
      and emits one SSE event per JSON-path-tagged token chunk. The carrier for those
      chunks is the new `FieldDelta` variant on `AnalysisChunk` â€” the canonical SSE
      envelope already used by Summarize, Builder, Insights, and Playbook flows.

      Choosing to EXTEND `AnalysisChunk` (vs introducing a parallel envelope) was an
      explicit R5 design decision per design.md Â§4.3 and is enforced by R5 Â§3.1's
      "Specifically prohibited" list. The variant is additive: existing serialized
      payloads remain byte-identical (the new `Delta` property is `null` and omitted),
      existing factory methods preserve their output shapes, and unknown discriminants
      are already ignored by the LegalWorkspace `streamSummarize()` parser. NFR-10
      makes this back-compat contract binding.

      The task is small (single-file model edit + tests + size verification) but it is
      load-bearing â€” task 006 (Structured Outputs + incremental parser) is the next
      critical-path task and depends on the variant shape this task ships.
    </background>
